    <bioghist>
      <head>Biographical/Historical Information</head>
      <p>The Farmers Mutual Fire Association of Chester, Virginia
         was originally incorporated under the laws of the Commonwealth
         of Virginia on 10 August 1895 as the Farmers Mutual Benefit
         Association of Virginia, and its offices were located in
         Richmond.</p>
      <p>The Association was reorganized under and amended charter
         and by-laws on 24 February 1898, and the office was moved to
         Chester. George E. Robertson was the first president, and
         Charles N. Friend was elected general agent, secretary and
         treasurer, which offices he held until his death on 16 June
         1919.</p>
      <p>The company insured dwellings, churches, stores, public
         garages, mills, motels, public halls, barns, grain, hay,
         livestock, machinery, and farm implements. Originally, the
         Association issued perpetual policies, and assessments were
         made as losses occured. Later, the company adopted the plan of
         issuing one, three, and five year policies with assessments
         being made yearly in advance.</p>
      <p>In 1952, the charter was again amended, and the name of the
         company was changed to the Farmers Mutual Fire Association. It
         operated state-wide, but its principal area of business was
         within ten counties surrounding Chesterfield. Its assets were
         liquidated in 1979.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent>
      <head>Scope and Content Information</head>
      <p>Records, 1895-1979, of the Farmers Mutual Fire Association
         of Chester, Virginia. Includes accounts and receipts, bank
         books, cancelled checks, charters and by-laws, correspondence,
         financial reports, minutes, distribution and receipt ledgers,
         and liquidation papers.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement>
      <head>Organization</head>
      <p>Organized into the following three series: Series I.
         Correspondence and Subject Files; Series II. Minutes; Series
         III. Ledgers.</p>
    </arrangement>
